Files:
- plugins/tumblr/src/tumblr-api.ts (change CSRF logic around lines 121-123)

Context:
Current code (lines 118-125 approximately):
  if (method !== 'GET') {
    const freshCsrf = await refreshCsrf(auth.apiToken);
    headers['X-Csrf'] = freshCsrf;
  }

The TumblrAuth object (from getAuthCache) includes a csrfToken field. After each request, updateCsrf() is called with the response X-Csrf header (lines 143-147), keeping it current. So the cached token is already kept up-to-date.

Fix:
  if (method !== 'GET') {
    // Use cached CSRF token; refresh only if empty
    const csrf = auth.csrfToken || await refreshCsrf(auth.apiToken);
    headers['X-Csrf'] = csrf;
  }

Or even simpler — since every response updates the cached CSRF via updateCsrf(), and getAuth() reads from the auth cache, after the first successful request the cache always has a fresh CSRF. Just use auth.csrfToken directly:
  if (method !== 'GET') {
    const csrf = auth.csrfToken;
    if (csrf) {
      headers['X-Csrf'] = csrf;
    } else {
      // First write with no cached CSRF — fetch it
      headers['X-Csrf'] = await refreshCsrf(auth.apiToken);
    }
  }

Make sure to read the full TumblrAuth interface and updateCsrf() implementation to understand how the cached csrfToken is stored and retrieved. The auth object must be updated (re-set in auth cache) when updateCsrf() runs, or the fix needs to directly access the cached auth and update it.

Constraints:
- Do NOT remove refreshCsrf() — it is still needed as a fallback when no cached CSRF exists
- Do NOT change the response header CSRF update logic (lines 143-147)
- The fix must handle the case where the csrfToken field is initially empty (first write in a session)
